Let me try a different approach. Maybe the issue is that there's a missing optimization somewhere. Let me check if the select optimization is missing.

Looking at the pattern:
```
%not. = xor i1 %1, true
%common.ret1.op = select i1 %not., i1 %2, i1 false
```

This is `select (xor %1, true), %2, false`.

At lines 4289-4296 of InstCombineSelect.cpp:
```cpp
Value *NotCond;
if (match(CondVal, m_Not(m_Value(NotCond))) &&
    !InstCombiner::shouldAvoidAbsorbingNotIntoSelect(SI)) {
  replaceOperand(SI, 0, NotCond);
  SI.swapValues();
  SI.swapProfMetadata();
  return &SI;
}
```

This transforms `select (not X), A, B` to `select X, B, A`.

For our case:
- CondVal = %not. = xor %1, true (which is equivalent to not %1)
- NotCond = %1
- A = %2
- B = false

After transformation:
- select %1, false, %2

If %1 == %2 (after trunc optimization), this becomes `select %1, false, %1`.

At InstructionSimplify.cpp lines 4927-4929:
```cpp
// select i1 X, i1 false, i1 X --> false
if (match(TrueVal, m_ZeroInt()))
  return ConstantInt::getFalse(Cond->getType());
```

This is inside the block:
```cpp
if (Cond == FalseVal) {
  // select i1 X, i1 true, i1 X --> X (logical-or)
  if (match(TrueVal, m_One()))
    return Cond;
  // select i1 X, i1 false, i1 X --> false
  if (match(TrueVal, m_ZeroInt()))
    return ConstantInt::getFalse(Cond->getType());
}
```

So the optimization chain depends on the trunc being transformed to icmp first, then the select condition being recognized as a negation, and finally the select simplifying when the true and false values match. I should verify whether the select pattern is actually being recognized and applied, or if the trunc transformation is failing to occur.

